ng rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":23,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":48,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":61,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Simon Warde was born in 1267, in Guiseley, Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir William De la Warde of Guiseley, was 47 and his mother, Margaret Neville, was 33. He married Claris before 1303, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. In 1274, at the age of 7, his occupation is listed as justice of ripon. He died in 1334, in his hometown, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1267–1334":"1267–1334","1255–1301":"1255–1301","1267–1328":"1267–1328","1283–1334":"1283–1334","1285–1346":"1285–1346","1287–1362":"1287–